% ===========================================================================
% ABSTRACT
% ===========================================================================
\begin{abstract}
Porting concurrent code across architectures is dangerous: programs correct on x86 (TSO)
silently break on ARM, RISC-V, or GPUs due to weaker memory ordering guarantees.
Existing tools model individual architectures but do not directly answer the
practitioner's question: \emph{``Is my code safe to port from architecture~$A$ to
architecture~$B$, and if not, what is the minimum fix?''}

We present \litmus{}, a portability checker that answers this question for
57 structurally distinct litmus test patterns across 10 architecture models
(4~CPU, 6~GPU with scoped synchronization), yielding 570 test-model pairs
analyzed in under 150\,ms. \litmus{} also includes a code analyzer that
extracts concurrency patterns from C/C++/CUDA source code and maps them
to known litmus patterns, achieving 75\% accuracy on 12 real-world code
snippets. The tool provides three capabilities unavailable in any single
existing tool: (1)~\textbf{GPU scope mismatch detection}---identifying
11 patterns where code safe on all CPUs fails on GPUs due to insufficient
synchronization scope; (2)~\textbf{per-thread minimal fence
recommendation} with architecture-specific fence types, achieving
25--88\% cost reduction over coarse barriers; (3)~\textbf{model boundary
analysis} identifying the exact patterns that discriminate adjacent
memory models.

We validate \litmus{} against expected results from \texttt{herd7}'s
\texttt{.cat} specifications (50/50 agreement on CPU test-model pairs)
and published hardware observations from the memory model testing
literature (25/25 consistency). We demonstrate practical utility through
12 real-world case studies---including lock-free queues, DPDK ring
buffers, crossbeam epoch reclamation, and CUDA scope mismatches---where
\litmus{} correctly identifies portability bugs in 9/12 cases via
automated code analysis.
\end{abstract}

% ===========================================================================
% 1. INTRODUCTION
% ===========================================================================
\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}

Modern concurrent software must run on increasingly diverse hardware:
server code written for x86 is deployed on ARM-based cloud instances
(AWS Graviton, Ampere Altra) and RISC-V embedded platforms; GPU compute
kernels target NVIDIA CUDA, AMD ROCm, and portable APIs (OpenCL, Vulkan).
Each architecture implements a different \emph{memory model} that
determines which reorderings of memory operations are
observable~\cite{Adve2010, Alglave2014}.

The practical consequences are severe. Consider a lock-free
single-producer, single-consumer (SPSC) queue---a fundamental building
block in systems like DPDK, Folly, and crossbeam:

\begin{lstlisting}[language=C, caption={SPSC queue: safe on x86, broken on ARM}]
// Producer (Thread 0)        // Consumer (Thread 1)
data = value;                 if (flag) {
flag = 1;                         use(data); // May see stale data!
                              }
\end{lstlisting}

On x86, Total Store Order (TSO) guarantees that the store to
\texttt{data} is visible before the store to \texttt{flag}. On ARM, both
stores may be reordered, and the consumer may observe \texttt{flag==1}
while reading stale \texttt{data}. This is the classic Message Passing
(MP) litmus test pattern, and \litmus{} detects it in under 1\,ms:

\begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption={Detecting the SPSC bug with \litmus{}}]
from code_analyzer import check_code_portability
bugs = check_code_portability(spsc_code, target_arch="arm")
# Returns: pattern=mp, fix="dmb ishst (T0); dmb ishld (T1)"
# Cost savings: 62.5% vs full dmb ish on both threads
\end{lstlisting}

GPU kernels face an additional dimension: \emph{scoped synchronization},
where fences only guarantee ordering within a specific scope (workgroup,
device, or system). A CUDA kernel using \texttt{\_\_threadfence\_block()}
(CTA-scoped) silently fails when threads in different CTAs
communicate~\cite{Sorensen2016, Alglave2015GPU}. \litmus{} is the first
tool to unify CPU portability checking with GPU scope mismatch detection
in a single framework.

\paragraph{Contributions.}
\begin{itemize}[nosep]
\item \textbf{Unified CPU+GPU portability checking}: 57 litmus test
      patterns across 10 architecture models (4 CPU, 6 GPU), producing
      570 test-model pairs analyzed in under 150\,ms
      (Section~\ref{sec:experiments}).
\item \textbf{Code-to-pattern analysis}: Automated extraction of
      concurrency patterns from C/C++/CUDA source code, achieving 75\%
      top-3 accuracy on 12 real-world snippets
      (Section~\ref{sec:code-analysis}).
\item \textbf{GPU scope mismatch detection}: 11 patterns where CPU-safe
      code fails on GPUs, including 6 critical bugs undetectable by
      CPU-only tools (Section~\ref{sec:gpu-scope}).
\item \textbf{Per-thread minimal fence analysis}: Architecture-specific
      recommendations with 25--88\% cost savings
      (Section~\ref{sec:fence-cost}).
\item \textbf{Model boundary analysis}: Precise identification of which
      patterns discriminate adjacent models
      (Section~\ref{sec:boundaries}).
\item \textbf{Validated correctness}: 50/50 agreement with expected
      \texttt{herd7} results and 25/25 consistency with published
      hardware observations (Section~\ref{sec:validation}).
\end{itemize}

% ===========================================================================
% 2. BACKGROUND
% ===========================================================================
\section{Background}
\label{sec:background}

\subsection{Axiomatic Memory Models}

We adopt the axiomatic framework of Alglave et al.~\cite{Alglave2014},
where an \emph{execution} is a graph
$E = (W, R, \po, \rf, \co)$ consisting of write events~$W$, read
events~$R$, program order~$\po$, reads-from~$\rf$, and coherence
order~$\co$.

\begin{definition}[Memory Model]
\label{def:memmodel}
A memory model $M$ is a predicate $M(E) \in \{\mathit{allowed},
\mathit{forbidden}\}$ over executions. An execution $E$ is
\emph{consistent} under~$M$ iff $M(E) = \mathit{allowed}$.
\end{definition}

\begin{definition}[Portability Safety]
\label{def:portsafe}
A litmus test pattern $P$ with forbidden outcome $F_P$ is \emph{safe}
to port from model $M_A$ to model $M_B$ iff: for every execution $E$
of $P$ that is consistent under $M_B$ and produces outcome $F_P$, there
exists an execution $E'$ of $P$ that is consistent under $M_A$ and also
produces $F_P$. Equivalently, if $F_P$ is forbidden under $M_A$
(no consistent execution produces it), then $F_P$ must also be forbidden
under $M_B$.
\end{definition}

\begin{remark}
Definition~\ref{def:portsafe} is pattern-specific: it concerns the
forbidden outcome $F_P$ of the specific pattern $P$, not all forbidden
outcomes of model $M_A$. This is the semantically correct formulation
for portability checking.
\end{remark}

\subsection{Supported Architecture Models}

\litmus{} implements 10 architecture models organized by increasing
permissiveness.

\paragraph{CPU models.}
\begin{itemize}[nosep]
\item \textbf{x86/TSO}~\cite{OwensSarkarSewell2009}: Only store$\to$load
      reordering is allowed. Multi-copy atomic.
\item \textbf{SPARC/PSO}: Adds store$\to$store reordering. Multi-copy atomic.
\item \textbf{ARM/ARMv8}~\cite{Pulte2018}: All four reordering types
      allowed. Not multi-copy atomic. Preserves address, data, and
      control dependencies.
\item \textbf{RISC-V/RVWMO}~\cite{RISCV2019}: Similar to ARM but with
      asymmetric fences (\texttt{fence~pred,succ}) and different
      dependency preservation rules.
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{GPU models.}
Each GPU API provides scoped synchronization at two levels:
\begin{itemize}[nosep]
\item \textbf{OpenCL}~\cite{Sorensen2016}: Workgroup and Device scope.
\item \textbf{Vulkan}~\cite{KhronosVulkan}: Workgroup and Device scope.
\item \textbf{PTX/CUDA}~\cite{Lustig2019}: CTA and GPU scope.
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{Model strength ordering.}

\begin{proposition}[Model Strength Hierarchy]
\label{prop:strength}
For CPU models:
$\mathrm{SC} \sqsubseteq \mathrm{TSO} \sqsubseteq \mathrm{PSO}
\sqsubseteq \mathrm{ARM}$.
RISC-V is comparable to ARM but not identical: ARM $\sqsubseteq$
RISC-V for 56 of 57 patterns in our suite, with a single discriminator
(\texttt{mp\_fence\_wr}) where ARM is safe but RISC-V is not, due to
differing fence semantics (Section~\ref{sec:boundaries}).
For each GPU API, device scope is strictly stronger than workgroup
scope: $\mathrm{GPU\text{-}Dev} \sqsubseteq \mathrm{GPU\text{-}WG}$.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
The CPU ordering follows from the set inclusion of preserved program
order edges: TSO preserves all $\po$ except $W \po R$ to different
addresses; PSO additionally relaxes $W \po W$; ARM relaxes all
cross-address $\po$ except dependency-ordered pairs. For GPU models,
any fence effective at workgroup scope is also effective at device scope
(which additionally covers cross-workgroup communication). The
ARM/RISC-V near-equivalence is verified empirically: of 57 patterns,
56 have identical safety classifications; the sole exception is
\texttt{mp\_fence\_wr} (see Section~\ref{sec:boundaries}).
\end{proof}

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[
  node distance=1.2cm and 1.5cm,
  every node/.style={draw, rounded corners, minimum width=1.6cm,
    minimum height=0.7cm, font=\small},
  arr/.style={-{Stealth[length=5pt]}, thick}
]
\node (sc) {SC};
\node[right=of sc] (tso) {TSO};
\node[right=of tso] (pso) {PSO};
\node[right=of pso] (arm) {ARM};
\node[above right=0.5cm and 1cm of arm] (riscv) {RISC-V};

\node[below=1.5cm of pso] (gpudev) {GPU-Dev};
\node[right=of gpudev] (gpuwg) {GPU-WG};

\draw[arr] (sc) -- node[above,draw=none,minimum width=0pt,minimum height=0pt,font=\scriptsize] {$\sqsubseteq$} (tso);
\draw[arr] (tso) -- node[above,draw=none,minimum width=0pt,minimum height=0pt,font=\scriptsize] {$\sqsubseteq$} (pso);
\draw[arr] (pso) -- node[above,draw=none,minimum width=0pt,minimum height=0pt,font=\scriptsize] {$\sqsubseteq$} (arm);
\draw[arr,dashed] (arm) -- node[right,draw=none,minimum width=0pt,minimum height=0pt,font=\scriptsize] {$\approx$} (riscv);
\draw[arr] (gpudev) -- node[above,draw=none,minimum width=0pt,minimum height=0pt,font=\scriptsize] {$\sqsubseteq$} (gpuwg);
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{Memory model strength hierarchy. Solid arrows denote strict
ordering ($\sqsubseteq$); dashed arrow denotes near-equivalence
($\approx$, identical on 56/57 patterns). GPU models are orthogonal
to CPU models: code safe on all CPUs may fail on GPUs due to scope
mismatches.}
\label{fig:hierarchy}
\end{figure}

% ===========================================================================
% 3. TOOL DESIGN
% ===========================================================================
\section{Tool Design}
\label{sec:design}

\subsection{Architecture Overview}

\litmus{} consists of three components: (1) the \emph{portability
engine} (\texttt{portcheck.py}, 1,732 lines), which performs brute-force
outcome enumeration and fence analysis for litmus test patterns;
(2) the \emph{code analyzer} (\texttt{code\_analyzer.py}, 1,031 lines),
which extracts memory operation patterns from real code and matches them
against the 57 built-in patterns; and (3) the \emph{API layer}
(\texttt{api.py}, 636 lines), providing a programmatic interface.

\begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption={Core API}]
from portcheck import check_portability
from code_analyzer import analyze_code, check_code_portability

# Pattern-based: check named litmus test
results = check_portability("mp", target_arch="arm")

# Code-based: extract patterns from real code
analysis = analyze_code(my_code, language="c")
bugs = check_code_portability(my_code, target_arch="arm")
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{Litmus Test Representation}

Each pattern is a set of typed memory operations (\texttt{MemOp})
with thread assignment, address, optional scope, optional dependency
type (address, data, control), and optional asymmetric fence
specification (predecessor/successor sets for RISC-V):

\begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption={MemOp dataclass}]
@dataclass
class MemOp:
    thread: int; optype: str  # 'store', 'load', 'fence'
    addr: str; scope: str = None  # 'workgroup', 'device'
    dep_on: str = None  # 'addr', 'data', 'ctrl'
    fence_pred: str = None  # RISC-V: 'r','w','rw'
    fence_succ: str = None
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{Portability Checking Algorithm}

For each (pattern, architecture) pair, \litmus{} performs brute-force
outcome enumeration: it generates all possible reads-from and coherence
order assignments, checks each against the architecture's ordering
constraints via cycle detection in the global happens-before relation,
and determines whether the pattern's forbidden outcome is allowed.

The consistency check considers: (1)~preserved program order (filtered
by model), (2)~fence effectiveness including GPU scope checking,
(3)~dependency preservation (ARM/RISC-V preserve addr/data/ctrl
dependencies), (4)~multi-copy atomicity, and (5)~RISC-V asymmetric
fence pred/succ sets.

\begin{theorem}[Soundness]
\label{thm:soundness}
If \litmus{} reports that pattern $P$ is safe to port from $M_A$ to
$M_B$, then indeed the forbidden outcome $F_P$ is forbidden under $M_B$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
\litmus{} enumerates \emph{all} possible executions (all reads-from and
coherence-order assignments) and checks each for consistency under $M_B$.
If no consistent execution produces $F_P$, the tool reports ``safe.''
Since the enumeration is exhaustive over the finite execution space of
the litmus test, no consistent execution producing $F_P$ is missed.
Therefore, if the tool reports safe, $F_P$ is genuinely forbidden under
$M_B$.

Note: soundness holds for the model implemented in the tool. If the
tool's model is more permissive than the actual hardware (i.e., the tool
allows executions that hardware does not), then the tool may report
``unsafe'' for patterns that are actually safe on hardware (false
positives), but will never miss a real bug (no false negatives).
\end{proof}

\subsection{Per-Thread Fence Recommendation}

When a pattern is unsafe on a target architecture, \litmus{} computes
the per-thread minimal fence insertion by analyzing which specific
operation-type pairs (W$\to$W, W$\to$R, R$\to$R, R$\to$W) are
relaxed on each thread and selecting the cheapest fence that restores
the needed ordering:

\begin{itemize}[nosep]
\item \textbf{ARM}: \texttt{dmb ishst} (store-only, cost 1),
      \texttt{dmb ishld} (load-only, cost 1), or \texttt{dmb ish}
      (full, cost 4).
\item \textbf{RISC-V}: \texttt{fence w,w} (cost 1), \texttt{fence r,r}
      (cost 1), \texttt{fence w,r} (cost 2), or \texttt{fence rw,rw}
      (full, cost 8).
\end{itemize}

\begin{theorem}[Fence Minimality]
\label{thm:fence-min}
The per-thread fence recommendation is minimal in the sense that no
strictly weaker fence type suffices to restore the required ordering
for the specific operation pairs on each thread.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
For each thread $t$, the algorithm computes the set of violated ordering
pairs $V_t \subseteq \{(W,W), (W,R), (R,R), (R,W)\}$. The fence
selection follows a deterministic mapping:
\begin{itemize}[nosep]
\item If $V_t = \{(W,W)\}$: \texttt{dmb ishst} on ARM (orders only W$\to$W).
      Using \texttt{dmb ishld} would not order stores.
\item If $V_t \subseteq \{(R,R), (R,W)\}$: \texttt{dmb ishld} on ARM.
      Using \texttt{dmb ishst} would not order loads.
\item If $V_t$ contains both store and load orderings: \texttt{dmb ish}
      (full) is required.
\end{itemize}
Analogous reasoning applies for RISC-V asymmetric fences. The fence
type selected is the weakest (cheapest) fence whose ordering guarantees
cover all pairs in $V_t$.
\end{proof}

\subsection{Code-to-Pattern Analysis}
\label{sec:code-analysis-design}

The code analyzer bridges the gap between real source code and
\litmus{}'s pattern database. It operates in three phases:

\begin{enumerate}[nosep]
\item \textbf{Parsing}: Regex-based extraction of memory operations
      from C/C++ (\texttt{std::atomic}, \texttt{volatile}), CUDA
      (\texttt{\_\_threadfence}, \texttt{\_\_syncthreads}), and
      pseudocode (store/load notation). Thread boundaries are detected
      from comments, function signatures, or \texttt{||} delimiters.
\item \textbf{Signature computation}: Each extracted operation sequence
      is characterized by thread count, per-thread operation types,
      shared variable patterns, fence presence, and GPU scope.
\item \textbf{Pattern matching}: The code signature is compared against
      all 57 built-in pattern signatures using a weighted similarity
      metric (thread count, operation sequence, store/load counts,
      fence presence, scope). Matches above a 0.3 confidence threshold
      are returned ranked by score.
\end{enumerate}

\paragraph{Limitations.} The code analyzer uses regex-based parsing,
not AST analysis. It cannot handle complex control flow, indirect memory
access, or template-heavy C++ code. It is designed for the common case
of recognizable concurrent idioms (message passing, store buffering,
mutual exclusion patterns) expressed in straightforward code.

% ===========================================================================
% 4. EXPERIMENTAL EVALUATION
% ===========================================================================
\section{Experimental Evaluation}
\label{sec:experiments}

All experiments were run on an Apple M2 machine with Python 3.11.
Results are reproducible via the commands in
Appendix~\ref{app:reproducibility}. All data files are saved in
\texttt{paper\_results\_v2/}.

\subsection{Full Portability Analysis}
\label{sec:portability}

We analyzed all 57 patterns across all 10 architectures, yielding
570 test-model pairs. Of these, \textbf{278 (48.8\%) are safe} and
\textbf{292 (51.2\%) exhibit portability bugs}. CPU-only pairs (228)
have a 51.8\% safety rate; GPU-only pairs (342) have a lower 46.8\%
rate, reflecting the additional scope-related failure modes.

